VM usic aficionados of Palakkad were treated to a three-day musical fete in connection with a memorial music festival for mridangam maestro Subbayyar (Palakkad Maniayyar's guru), at Prasanna Mahaganapathi Temple, Chathapuram.Savitha Sreeram, a versatile vocalist from Chennai, enchanted listeners with her mellifluous voice and crystal-clear padanthara on the first day of the festival. The vocalist was skilfully accompanied by Kodunthirappulli Subbaraman on the violin and A. Ganesan on the mridangam.Starting on a lilting noteSavitha began her concert with a lilting Adi tala varna &#8216;Jalajaksha' in Hamsadhwani. She then moved on to a Dikshithar kriti &#8216;Vallabhanayakasya' in Begada, set to Roopaka tala. A melting alapana of Bhoopala and the pensive Swati kriti &#8216;Gopalaka Pahimamanisam,' embellished with Srothovahakayathi and rhythmic jathis, enchanted the audience.A scholarly rendition of Papanasam Sivan's &#8216;Parvathi Nayakane saranam' in Shanmukhapriya was bhava laden and had niraval and kalpanaswara. This was followed by a fast rendition of Swati Tirunal's &#8216;Bhogeendra sayinam' in Khandhachappu tala. Next came the highlight of the concert &#8211; a luxuriant elaboration of Kamboji, which brought to fore the essence of the raga with subtle gamakas.Subbaraman's essay of the raga was complementary with melodic sancharas. Tyagaraja's &#8216;Evvarimatta,' was embellished with well-articulated improvisations and vivacious kalpanaswara at the lyrical sequence &#8216;Paramabhagavatha&#8230;.' This was followed by an excellent tani.A haunting Ragamalika sloka &#8216;Kasthurithilakam,' was followed by &#8216;Bhavayami Gopalabalam' in Yamunakalyani and the popular Marathi Abhang &#8216;Bhakthajanavalasale.' Savitha concluded the recital with &#8216;Sreerama Jayamangalam.'Thenkarai Maharajan teamed up with Nedumangad Sivanandan (violin), Palakkad Krishnamoorthy (mridangam),Thripunithura Radahkrishana (ghatam) and Kannazha Vasudevan (ganjira) to captivate rasikas with rare compositions and old melodies. Two rare compositions of Balamuralikrishna &#8211; &#8216;Omkarapranavodbhava' in Shanmukhapriya and &#8216;Pirayaniyum perumanmakan' in Hamsadhvani started the concert on a magnificent note.Poignant renditionA poignant rendition of Tyagaraja's &#8216;Raghuveera ranadheera' in Huseni and Papanasam Sivan's &#8216;Nee irankayenil' in Adhana paved the way to a spirited Sahana. This was followed by Sivan's &#8216;Chitham Irangathenayya.'A fast number &#8216;Manavyalakim,' Tyagaraja's composition in Nalinakanthi, was rendered before the main item of the day, an expansive alapana of Bhairavi, illustrating the very subtle nuances of the raga and the rakthi of the raga in melodious sancharas. Sivanandan portrayed the ragas Sahana and Bhairavi with sparkling sancharas.Patnam Subrammanyayyar's &#8216;Nee padamulegathi,' set to Adi tala (two kala), had a niraval at &#8216;Kamithaphaladayaki. The vocalist laid emphasis on the sahithyabhava of the piece during his rendition. This was followed by a vibrant tani. Maharajan concluded the concert with a Mangalam of Balamuralikrushna &#8211; &#8216;Ramachandraya.'N.J. Nandini shared the stage with Nedumangad Sivanandan (violin), Guruvayoor Sanoj (mridangam), Thiruvananthapuram Manoj (ghatam) and Kannazha Vasudevan (ganjira) during her performance on the final day of the fete. Her recital provided a promising account of her artistic talent.The main item of the concert, a resplendent Thodi and a rare composition of Tyagaraja, &#8216;Dasukorvalena,' set to Misrajhampa tala, was decorated with well-structured niraval and swara strings. The concert ended with a mangalam, &#8216;Prahlada Naradai.'
